  "id": "MAL-2026-5289",
  "summary": "Malicious code in unifi-portal (npm)",
  "details": "\n---\n_-= Per source details. Do not edit below this line.=-_\n\n## Source: amazon-inspector (bcc805dd8053a750065e3593713b863e253ff746194f6d1fc6bcebeb73c0b43a)\nindex.js imports `os` and `https` and, on module load, collects `os.hostname()`, `os.userInfo()`, and `os.networkInterfaces()` and transmits the data via `https.get` to an external destination referenced as hackerone.com. The version number (99.0.0) and package naming pattern are consistent with dependency-confusion research/PoC payloads targeting an internal `unifi-portal` namespace; in a victim build that resolves to the public registry, installing or requiring this package leaks host identity and network topology to a third party. Regardless of whether the recipient is a researcher or a malicious actor, the package's only behavior is unsolicited collection and exfiltration of installer host metadata.\n\n## Source: ossf-package-analysis (8ff224f10cd94268bd5347ea6898f0cb1c54d23b19a6eb02d8efa268a16e15e8)\nThe OpenSSF Package Analysis project identified 'unifi-portal' @ 99.0.0 (npm) as malicious.\n\nIt is considered malicious because:\n\n- The package communicates with a domain associated with malicious activity.\n",
